# LandslideKR — Post-hoc FAR-filter Analysis Report

Date: 2026-04-14 (three-event extension 2026-04-14 22:00 KST)
Scope: Re-evaluate the three-event benchmark (Pohang 2022, Yecheon 2023, Chuncheon 2020) under 9 post-hoc filter configurations intended to reduce false alarms, and report precision lift over base rate — the operationally meaningful axis given the severe class imbalance (positives at 0.12 – 1.65 %).

**Provenance note (2026-04-14).** This report was initially written for the two-event (Pohang, Yecheon) benchmark; the Chuncheon 2020 third event was added to the benchmark later the same day. The `far_filter_results.json` and `far_filter_results.csv` bundles in this directory are three-event (authoritative); the prose below retains its original two-event framing and should be read as the two-event core narrative. For the three-event synthesis, see the integrated manuscript `../draft/_integrated_v06_draft.md` §3.5 and appendix Table 6 (which use the three-event JSON/CSV directly).

## 1. Analysis question

Can post-hoc filters (hillslope mask, probability quantile gates, slope gates, compound) meaningfully reduce false alarms on the LandslideKR baseline predictions without collapsing detection recall? Which event-filter combinations yield operationally useful precision improvements?

## 2. Data validated

- `out/pohang_2022/prob_unstable.tif`, `consensus_label.tif`, `dem_utm.tif` — 912 384 valid pixels, 1 099 positives (0.12 %).
- `out/extreme_rainfall_2023/prob_unstable.tif`, `consensus_label.tif`, `dem_utm.tif` — 11 113 520 valid pixels, 183 507 positives (1.65 %).
- Sklearn ROC-AUC confirmed on raster re-reads: Pohang 0.612, Yecheon 0.449 (matches published log runs).
- Unit of analysis: **pixel**, per event. Each pixel is scored independently; no run-level seeds because the SHALSTAB MC has already been averaged to a single `prob_unstable.tif` per event.
- **Blocker for inferential statistics across methods on a per-pixel basis**: pixels are not independent (spatial autocorrelation). Reported numbers are descriptive only; no p-values or CIs are claimed at pixel level.

## 3. Key finding — raw FAR is not the right communicator

At positive-class rates of 0.12 % (Pohang) and 1.65 % (Yecheon), any filter that keeps > 2 % of pixels as predicted-unstable will have FAR ≈ 98 %. FAR varies trivially across all nine filters (Pohang 0.998 → 0.999; Yecheon 0.977 → 0.990) because the denominator (predicted_positives) is always dominated by the non-scar class. Reporting raw FAR as the FAR-reduction axis gives a false impression of stasis.

The operationally meaningful axis is **precision lift over base rate**:

> `lift = precision_in_filtered_region / base_rate_in_AOI`

Lift > 1.0 means the filter concentrates true positives beyond random. Lift ≈ 1.0 means the filter is no better than random. Lift < 1.0 means the filter removes more true positives than false positives — it is actively harmful.

## 4. Results

### Pohang 2022 (base rate 0.1205 %)

| Filter                           | POD   | Precision | Lift    | Kept-fraction |
|----------------------------------|-------|-----------|---------|---------------|
| F0 baseline                      | 0.914 | 0.00158   | 1.31×   | 69.6 %        |
| F1 hillslope                     | 0.208 | 0.00174   | 1.44×   | 14.4 %        |
| F2 prob top-10 %                 | 0.692 | 0.00156   | 1.30×   | 53.3 %        |
| F3 prob top-5 %                  | 0.692 | 0.00156   | 1.30×   | 53.3 %        |
| F4 prob top-1 %                  | 0.692 | 0.00156   | 1.30×   | 53.3 %        |
| F5 F1 ∩ top-10 %                 | 0.065 | 0.00188   | **1.56×** | 4.15 %     |
| F6 F1 ∩ top-5 %                  | 0.065 | 0.00188   | **1.56×** | 4.15 %     |
| F7 slope > 20°                   | 0.049 | 0.00120   | 1.00×   | 4.93 %        |
| F8 F1 ∩ slope > 20° ∩ prob > 0.9 | 0.023 | 0.00090   | 0.75×   | 3.04 %        |

- **Best lift**: F5/F6 (hillslope + top quantile) at 1.56× — but POD drops to 0.065 (93 % of positives lost).
- **Over-filtering hurts**: F8 lift = 0.75× (below random) — excessive compounding removes more TPs than FPs.
- **F0 baseline lift = 1.31×** is already weak; the model has only modest discrimination over random on Pohang at the pixel level, in line with ROC-AUC 0.612.
- **Quantile saturation**: F2/F3/F4 are identical. The SHALSTAB MC probability distribution has ≥10 % of pixels saturated at p = 1.0, so the top-1/5/10 % thresholds all collapse to the p = 1.0 tier. This is a bimodality artifact of the Monte Carlo ensemble, not a computational error.

### Yecheon 2023 (base rate 1.6512 %)

| Filter                           | POD   | Precision | Lift    | Kept-fraction |
|----------------------------------|-------|-----------|---------|---------------|
| F0 baseline                      | 0.484 | 0.01448   | 0.88×   | 55.2 %        |
| F1 hillslope                     | 0.417 | 0.02115   | 1.28×   | 32.5 %        |
| F2 prob top-10 %                 | 0.144 | 0.00968   | 0.59×   | 24.5 %        |
| F3 prob top-5 %                  | 0.144 | 0.00968   | 0.59×   | 24.5 %        |
| F4 prob top-1 %                  | 0.144 | 0.00968   | 0.59×   | 24.5 %        |
| F5 F1 ∩ top-10 %                 | 0.097 | 0.01913   | 1.16×   | 8.37 %        |
| F6 F1 ∩ top-5 %                  | 0.097 | 0.01913   | 1.16×   | 8.37 %        |
| F7 slope > 20°                   | 0.268 | 0.02339   | **1.42×** | 18.9 %     |
| F8 F1 ∩ slope > 20° ∩ prob > 0.9 | 0.122 | 0.02246   | 1.36×   | 8.95 %        |

- **Baseline is worse than random** (lift 0.88×) — confirms the rank-inversion finding in §3.1 of the manuscript.
- **Slope > 20° alone gives the best lift** (1.42×) with POD 0.268. Topographic gating outperforms SHALSTAB's own probability output.
- **Hillslope mask alone (F1) rescues lift from 0.88 to 1.28×** while retaining POD 0.417.
- **Probability quantile gating (F2-F4) makes Yecheon worse** — the top 24.5 % of probability values contain fewer scars per pixel than the baseline region. This is a direct consequence of the rank inversion.
- **Quantile saturation**: same as Pohang, F2/F3/F4 collapse.

## 5. Interpretation and what changes in belief

- The "apply a threshold to reduce FAR" intuition fails on imbalanced landslide susceptibility: raw FAR is structurally pinned near 99 % and cannot be the headline metric.
- The useful operational axis is **precision lift + recall + kept-fraction** reported jointly, as WildfireKR (IEEE Access 2026) does for Recall/IoU trade-offs.
- Adding the hillslope mask is a Pareto-defensible move on Yecheon (lift 0.88 → 1.28, POD 0.484 → 0.417). On Pohang it costs more recall than it buys precision.
- Slope > 20° is the most effective single-knob lift on Yecheon (1.42×) — this is the pixel-level analog of the §3.3 finding that slope-alone ranking AUC (0.669) beats SHALSTAB AUC (0.449).
- The SHALSTAB Monte Carlo probability is **not a calibrated ranking** — bimodality at p = 0 and p = 1 means quantile gating above p = 0.5 does nothing. A calibrated replacement (isotonic regression per lithology; or logistic on the MC counts) is needed before probability thresholding can contribute to FAR control.

